\begin{lemma}
\label{lem-Kramers}
Let ${\eta}=-1$. If ${\cal E}\subset{\cal K}$ is a finite dimensional subspace satisfying ${S}\,\overline{{\cal E}}={\cal E}$, then $\dim({\cal E})$ is even. 
\end{lemma}


\noindent {\bf Proof.} 
We construct iteratively subpaces ${\cal E}_{2n}=\mbox{\rm span}\{\psi_1,{S}\,\overline{\psi_1},\ldots,\psi_n,{S}\,\overline{\psi_n}\}$ of ${\cal E}$ of dimension $2n$. For $n=1$ choose some $\psi_1\in{\cal E}$. Suppose that $\psi_1=\mu {S}\, \overline{\psi_1}$ for some $\mu\not=0$. Then $\psi_1=\mu {S}\,\overline{(\mu {S}\, \overline{\psi_1})}=-|\mu|^2 \psi_1$ implying $\psi_1=0$. Hence either ${\cal E}$ is trivial or at least two-dimensional. Now let ${\cal E}_{2n}$ as above be given. Choose $\psi_{n+1}\in{\cal E}\setminus{\cal E}_{2n}$. By hypothesis, ${S}\,\overline{\psi_{2n+1}}\in{\cal E}$. Now define ${\cal E}_{2n+2}$ by the above formula. If $\dim({\cal E}_{2n+2})=2n+2$, one continues the iterative construction. If $\dim({\cal E}_{2n+2})=2n+1$, then ${S}\,\overline{\psi_{n+1}}=\mu\psi_{n+1}+\phi$ for some $\phi\in{\cal E}_{2n}$ and $\mu\in{\mathbb C}$. Hence with ${S}\,{\psi_{n+1}}=\overline{\mu}\,\overline{\psi_{n+1}}+\overline{\phi}$ and ${S}^2=-{\bf 1}$ implies

Now $\phi-\mu{S}\,\overline{\phi}\in{\cal E}_{2n}$ so that also ${S}\,\overline{\psi_{n+1}}\in{\cal E}_{2n}$. Using again that ${S}\,\overline{{\cal E}_{2n}}={\cal E}_{2n}$ follows that also $\psi_{n+1}\in{\cal E}_{2n}$, in contradiction to the above choice. In conclusion, either ${\cal E}={\cal E}_{2n}$ or ${\cal E}_{2n+2}\subset{\cal E}$. Hence the dimension of ${\cal E}$ is even. 
\hfill $\Box$


