(ii) Let us now consider the case $({\eta},{\tau})=(-1,-1)$. The argument is similar, so let us only focus on the differences. Then $u_-^*u_+-{\bf 1}= v_+^*s^*(s^*(v_+v_-^*)s(v_+v_-^*)^t-{\bf 1})sv_+$ is invertible so that $v=s^*(v_+v_-^*)s(v_+v_-^*)^t$ is a gapped odd symmetric unitary which can be deformed by a path of odd symmetric gapped unitaries $t\in[0,1]\mapsto v_t$ from $v_0=v$ to $v_1=-{\bf 1}$ (because the projection valued spectral measure is quaternionic). Lemma~\ref{lem-unitaryfactorize} gives a path $t\in[0,1]\mapsto w_t$ of gapped unitaries such that $v_t=s^*w_ts(w_t)^t$ and $w_1=\imath {\bf 1}$. Now $s^*w_0s(w_0)^t=s^*(v_+v_-^*)s(v_+v_-^*)^t$ so that $(v_+v_-^*)^*w_0=s^*\overline{(v_+v_-^*)^*w_0}s$ is quaterionic (recall that now $s^2=-{\bf 1}$). Hence there exists a path $t\in[-1,0]\mapsto q_t$ of quaterionic unitaries  such that $q_{-1}={\bf 1}$ and $q_{0}=(v_+v_-^*)^*w_0$. Setting $w_t=v_+v_-^*q_t$ for  $t\in[-1,0]$, concatenation yields a path $t\in[-1,1]\mapsto w_t$ from $w_{-1}=v_+v_-^*$ to $w_1=\imath{\bf 1}$. Next let us set $u_{+,t}=u_+$ and $u_{-,t}=w_t^*u_+\overline{w_t}$. Both are anti-symmetric unitaries and by construction the invertibility of $u_{-,t}^*u_{+,t}-{\bf 1}$ is guaranteed for all $t\in[-1,1]$. Furthermore, one checks $u_{-,1}=-u_+$ and $u_{-,-1}=u_-$. The associated projection $P_{\pm,1}$ is again of the form \eqref{eq-Ppmrep}. All these projections can homotopically deformed to the case $u_+=s$. Recall, however, that ${\mathbb F}{\mathbb H}({\cal K},{J},{S})$ has two components due to the first step of the proof.
\hfill $\Box$




\begin{coro}
\label{coro-AtiyahSinger}
Suppose the same hypothesis as in Theorem~\ref{theo-connectedReal}. The set of ${\mathbb F}{\mathbb H}({\cal K},{J},{S})$ has the following deformation retracts:

\begin{enumerate}[\rm (i)]

\item the set of real Fredholm operators for $({\eta},{\tau})=(1,1)$;

\item the set of anti-symmetric Fredholm operators for $({\eta},{\tau})=(-1,-1)$;

\item the set of quaternionic Fredholm operators for $({\eta},{\tau})=(-1,1)$;

\item the set of symmetric Fredholm operators for $({\eta},{\tau})=(1,-1)$.

\end{enumerate}

These sets are respectively the classifying spaces ${\mathbb F}_0$, ${\mathbb F}_2$, ${\mathbb F}_4$ and ${\mathbb F}_6$ for Real $K$-theory of Atiyah and Singer \cite{AS}.

\end{coro}


